    {
      "id": "c5ad75e91c359815b946cd43605d26e0ee11aa6a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2013-06-13 19:53:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI meant to post this comment with the initial patch submission, but it slipped my mind. The Cray engineer who authored this patch had this to say about autotools terminology.\n\n\"Either the original commit author for a0a72a9f47f85250cdbfdf4ef2e760425bd013ac is confused about how Autotools cross-compiling works, or I'm missing something unique about the lustre build.  Related to the architectures involved, there are three terms in autotools: build, host, target.  Build is where the compile is actually happening.  Host is the architecture of the binaries being produced by the compile.  And target is rarely used, except for compilers, to determine the architecture that the compiler being built targets (e.g., you could build a compiler on PPC (=build), but the compiler binaries really run on x86_64 (=host), but the built compiler itself produces ARM binaries (=target)).  Anyway, some of the lustre autotools code introduced in a0a72a9f47f85250cdbfdf4ef2e760425bd013ac makes use of the target family of variables.  I fixed this to use host instead.\"\n\nhttp://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gccint/Configure-Terms.html",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
